english:
  title: Memorial Declining the Position of Commander of the Northwestern Border Garrison
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Military affairs lie beyond the ken of scholars; how could one of feeble spirit presume to counsel generals? Hearing of this command fills me with both alarm and sorrow.

    Your servant is but discarded timber of the parasol tree, a vessel too small to hold the grains—having entered service in my prime, I have already failed to display any exceptional talent. Now old and useless, how could I possibly bear such grave responsibility? I have stolen honor and seized position without rendering service, and reflecting upon my own shortcomings, I recognize my incapacity. I wish only to retire in old age.

    Moreover, the people now suffer impoverishment and the state's resources are depleted; neighboring nations grow bold and their power waxes strong. This is no time for complacency and expedience—it demands action and purpose. Surely what is needed is one of this generation's finest minds, one whom all ten thousand would acclaim, to whom should be entrusted command beyond the gates, that military fortune may smile and calamity be prevented, that peace may be secured.

    But one such as I, mere ignorance and uselessness—I am superfluous.

    Your servant humbly begs that you cultivate virtue without indulgence, and in governing the realm, examine what is doubtful. Should you seek such capable men, be wary—for even the mighty Pang Kuai brought trouble in his wake. Better far is the counsel of Tu Mu on the art of war: that careful selection of talent is paramount. Let such men plan wisely to forestall calamity. When capable hands take charge, gradually shall prosperity be achieved. For one who knows himself is enlightened, and finds peace in his proper station.
  footnotes:
    - '樗櫟 (Parasol tree): An ancient metaphor for useless or humble talent, from Zhuangzi'
    - '斗筲 (Small vessels): A classical allusion to limited capacity; literally measuring vessels of small volume'
    - '閫外 (Beyond the gates): A military term meaning the authority to command beyond the defensive perimeter, suggesting independent military command'
    - '樊噲 (Pang Kuai): A general of the Han dynasty known for acting rashly'
    - '杜牧 (Tu Mu): A celebrated Tang dynasty general and strategist whose writings on military affairs were highly regarded'
